The Kan'iryō stipulates the correspondence between {{ill|government posts|ja|官職}} and {{ill|court ranks|ja|位階}}. It defines four ranks for princes, from {{ill|First Rank|ja|一品}} to {{ill|Fourth Rank|ja|四品}}, and 30 ranks for other royal family members and officials, from {{ill|Senior First Rank|ja|正一位|1=Senior First Rank}} to {{ill|Junior Initial Rank Lower|ja|少初位下}}. These ranks are linked to specific {{ill|Four-Tier Officials|ja|四等官}}, {{ill|honorary positions|ja|品官}}, and {{ill|supervisory roles|ja|長上}}.
The Kan'iryō corresponds to the {{ill|Tang Code's official rank system|ja|唐令の官品令}} but differs significantly in its application. In Tang China, ranks were divided into official grades (from {{ill|Zhengyi Pin|ja|正一品}} to {{ill|Congjiu Pinxia|ja|従九品下}}) as standards of hierarchical distinction and were not necessarily bestowed on officials. In contrast, under the Japanese system, court ranks were individually conferred, and holding a certain rank was a prerequisite for appointment to government posts, reflecting the unique {{ill|official rank correspondence system|ja|官位相当制|1=Kan'i sōtō system}} in Japan. This system had a more rigid class structure than its Chinese counterpart.
Additionally, the Kan'iryō regulated {{ill|merit ranks|ja|勲位}}, which were granted based on military achievements. There were twelve levels of merit ranks, and the code detailed their correspondence to court ranks for use in ceremonial settings, such as processions.
