'''Kan'iryō''' (官位令) is one of the chapters of the {{ill|Ritsuryō|ja|律令|12=draft|12=draft}} codes. In both the {{ill|Taihō Code|ja|大宝律令|12=draft|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Yōrō Code|ja|養老律令|12=draft|12=draft}}, it occupies the first position and is believed to consist of 19 articles.<ref>{{Cite book|和書 |title=The Achievements of Inoue Mitsusada and Research on "Ryōshūge" |year=2019 |publisher={{ill|Meiji University Institute of Ancient Japanese Studies|ja|明治大学日本古代学研究所|12=draft|12=draft}} |pages=35-41 |series=Formation of a Global Hub for Research on Ancient Japanese Studies |author={{ill|Yoshimura Takehiko|ja|吉村武彦|12=draft|12=draft}} |url=https://www.meiji.ac.jp/research/promote/strategic/6t5h7p00000rtjvy-att/a1559088837624.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|author=Sakagami Yasutoshi|year=1998|title=Three Studies on the Restoration of the Taihō Code |url=https://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/1867921/p001.pdf.pdf|journal={{ill|Shien|ja|史淵|12=draft|12=draft}}|volume=135|pages=1-17|publisher={{ill|Kyushu University Faculty of Letters|ja|九州大学文学部|12=draft|12=draft}}}}</ref>.

== Overview ==

The Kan'iryō stipulates the correspondence between {{ill|government posts|ja|官職|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|court ranks|ja|位階|12=draft|12=draft}}. It defines four ranks for princes, from {{ill|First Rank|ja|一品|12=draft|12=draft}} to {{ill|Fourth Rank|ja|四品|12=draft|12=draft}}, and 30 ranks for other royal family members and officials, from {{ill|Senior First Rank|ja|正一位|1=Senior First Rank|12=draft|12=draft}} to {{ill|Junior Initial Rank Lower|ja|少初位下|1=Lesser Initial Rank|lt=Lesser Initial Rank, Lower Grade|12=draft|12=draft}}. These ranks are linked to specific {{ill|Four-Tier Officials|ja|四等官|1=Shitōkan|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|honorary positions|ja|品官|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|supervisory roles|ja|長上|12=draft|12=draft}}.

The Kan'iryō corresponds to the {{ill|Tang Code's official rank system|ja|唐令の官品令|12=draft|12=draft}} but differs significantly in its application. In Tang China, ranks were divided into official grades (from {{ill|Zhengyi Pin|ja|正一品|12=draft|12=draft}} to {{ill|Congjiu Pinxia|ja|従九品下|12=draft|12=draft}}) as standards of hierarchical distinction and were not necessarily bestowed on officials. In contrast, under the Japanese system, court ranks were individually conferred, and holding a certain rank was a prerequisite for appointment to government posts, reflecting the unique {{ill|official rank correspondence system|ja|官位相当制|1=Kan'i sōtō system|12=draft|12=draft}} in Japan. This system had a more rigid class structure than its Chinese counterpart.

Additionally, the Kan'iryō regulated {{ill|merit ranks|ja|勲位|12=draft|12=draft}}, which were granted based on military achievements. There were twelve levels of merit ranks, and the code detailed their correspondence to court ranks for use in ceremonial settings, such as processions.

