The Kan'iryō stipulates the correspondence between {{ill|government posts|ja|官職|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/government posts|qq=}} and {{ill|court Ranks|ja|位階|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/court Ranks|qq=}}. It defines four Ranks for princes, from {{ill|First Rank|ja|一品|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/First Rank|qq=}} to {{ill|Fourth Rank|ja|四品|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fourth Rank|qq=}}, and 30 Ranks for other royal family members and officials, from {{ill|Senior First Rank|ja|正一位|1=Senior First Rank|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior First Rank|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior First Rank|qq=}} to {{ill|Junior Initial Rank Lower|ja|少初位下|1=Lesser Initial Rank|lt=Lesser Initial Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Initial Rank Lower|13=User:Immanuelle/Lesser Initial Rank|qq=}}. These Ranks are linked to specific {{ill|Four-Tier Officials|ja|四等官|1=Shitōkan|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Four-Tier Officials|13=User:Immanuelle/Shitōkan|qq=}}, {{ill|honorary positions|ja|品官|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/honorary positions|qq=}}, and {{ill|supervisory roles|ja|長上|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/supervisory roles|qq=}}.

The Kan'iryō corresponds to the {{ill|Tang Code's official Rank system|ja|唐令の官品令|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tang Code's official Rank system|qq=}} but differs significantly in its application. In Tang China, Ranks were divided into official grades (from {{ill|Zhengyi Pin|ja|正一品|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zhengyi Pin|qq=}} to {{ill|Congjiu Pinxia|ja|従九品下|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Congjiu Pinxia|qq=}}) as standards of hierarchical distinction and were not necessarily bestowed on officials. In contrast, under the Japanese system, court Ranks were individually conferred, and holding a certain Rank was a prerequisite for appointment to government posts, reflecting the unique [[:en:List of Japanese court ranks, positions and hereditary titles|Kan'i sōtō system]] in Japan. This system had a more rigid class structure than its Chinese counterpart.

Additionally, the Kan'iryō regulated {{ill|merit Ranks|ja|勲位|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/merit Ranks|qq=}}, which were granted based on military achievements. There were twelve levels of merit Ranks, and the code detailed their correspondence to court Ranks for use in ceremonial settings, such as processions.

